<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
<summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">üÜö Circuit Playground vs micro:bit</summary>
 <div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>

#### The **Circuit Playground** is a small microcontroller board with LEDs, buttons, and sensors built in. It is designed specifically for novice programmers, enabling students to get up and running quickly with physical computing without worrying about many of the traditional barriers to entry.

#### The **micro:bit** is a pocket-sized computer with an LED light display, buttons, sensors, and many input/output features that, when programmed, let students interact with the device and the world. The many built in features of the micro:bit allow beginners to do interesting things immediately without wiring. 

</p>
</div>
</details>

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
<summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">üîå How do these devices connect to App Lab?</summary>
 <div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>

## WebSerial

#### The Circuit Playground and micro:bit can connect directly to computers while using Google Chrome or Microsoft Edge browsers. WebSerial is the recommended way to connect to your board.

### **Set Up**

#### 1. Connect the board to your computer.
#### 2. Press the ‚ÄúConnect to Board‚Äù button.
#### 3. A window should pop up with a row that includes "Circuit Playground" or "micro:bit". Select that row, then click "Connect".
#### 4. You should see several green checkmarks below. When full connected, the Circuit Playground will display a sequence of green lights and emit a series of beeps, and the micro:bit will show a short animation.

#### That's it! Just those **four** easy steps! If you have any issues, please refer to our <a href="https://support.code.org/hc/en-us/articles/9953258694669" target="blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Support Article</a>.

</p>
</div>
